ral selection, but that in order to do so we must consider the role of development--or more precisely the role of life cycles--in evolutionary change. In a lively writing style that will be familiar to readers of his work The Evolution of Culture in Animals (Princeton, 1980), Bonner addresses a general audience interested in biology, as well as specialists in all areas of evolutionary biology. What is novel in the approach used here is the comparison of complexity inside the organism (especially cell differentiation) with the complexity outside (that is, within an ecological community). Matters of size at both these levels are closely related to complexity. The book shows how an understanding of the grand course of evolution can come from combining our knowledge of genetics, development, ecology, and even behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEvolution (Biology) 0aNatural selection. 0aevolucijaxdarwinizemxfosilixkompleksnostxvelikost telesaxzdružbexpopulacije. 0arazvojna biologijaxanatomijaxgostota naseljenostixrazporeditev naseljenostixetologija. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aDarwinian evolution.  aDictyostelium.  aHutchinson ratio.  aKirschner, M.  aLamarckism.  aaclonal organisms.  aacrasids.  aallostery.  aapical meristem.  abehavior.  acambium.  acell competition.  aconquest of land.  aconvergent evolution.  adevelopmental constraints.  adictyostelids.  adominance hierarchy.  aearthworms.  aecology.  aelastic similarity.  aendoskeleton.  aenergid.  afood chains.  agene net.  agenetic drift.  ahabituation, in Stentor.  aheterochrony.  aheterocysts.  ainductors, in development.  aintegrating mechanisms.  aisolating mechanisms.  ajellyfish.  akelp.  alichens.  aliverworts.  amacronucleus.  amammals.  